    "response": "Understanding diminishing returns in fire economics is critical for efficient resource allocation and effective fire management. Recognizing that greater investments do not equate to proportionally higher returns enables decision-makers to avoid wasteful spending on overly aggressive strategies that offer low incremental benefits. This understanding helps in identifying the optimal level of investment for achieving maximum fire prevention effectiveness without exhausting budgets. Moreover, it fosters a more strategic approach towards prioritizing less costly, high-impact interventions over those that, despite higher costs, result in minimal additional benefits. Ultimately, this comprehension aids in developing sustainable fire management practices that preserve community resources.",
