    "prompt": "According to the reading \"Mod02 FIRE Economics: Mod2HW\", what is diminishing return of investment in the context of fire economics, and can you provide three examples?",
    "response": "Diminishing return of investment in fire economics refers to the decrease in the additional benefits gained from increasing investment in fire prevention or mitigation measures. For example: 1) Adding more firefighters may initially significantly reduce response times and increase safety. However, after a certain point, adding more firefighters yields less improvement in response time or fire containment. 2) Investing in new fire trucks and equipment improves operational efficiency. Yet, beyond a threshold, purchasing additional equipment offers less value due to overlaps and redundancy. 3) Implementing extensive public awareness campaigns on fire safety initially leads to a substantial increase in community compliance with safety regulations. However, after achieving a certain level of awareness, additional investment generates diminishing returns in behavioral change.",
    "source_file": "C:\\Users\\wei\\OneDrive - Colostate\\Teaching\\NR444\\Mod02_FIRE_Economics\\Mod2HW.docx",
